#eNCA #DStv403  JOHANNESBURG - President Cyril Ramaphosa says he's cooperating with law enforcement agencies on an investigation into the theft of money at his Phala Phala farm and refuses to be distracted, intimidated or bullied into submission to leave his job as the country's first citizen.  eNCA's Govan Whittles reports. Courtesy of #DStv403  Ramaphosa delivered the keynote address at the SACP elective conference in his capacity as ANC President. READ: Ramaphosa farm theft | President given more time to respond "I have pledged my full cooperation to the investigation process that is underway," Ramaphosa said. "I am prepared to be held accountable. I opted of my own volition to appear before the Integrity Commission." Ramaphosa said a date will be finalised for a meeting. READ: Ramaphosa Farm Theft | Farm was not under SAPS guard - Cele "I would like to say I will not allow these allegations to deter me from what needs to be done, to rebuild our economy. "I will not allow this to deter me, to discourage me from the work that I have to do. "I will not be intimidated, nor distracted, nor bullied into submission." President Cyril Ramaphosa says he's cooperating with law enforcement agencies on an investigation into the theft of money at his Phala Phala farm and refuses to be distracted, intimidated or bullied into submission to leave his job as the country's first citizen. #dstv403